{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_iago_ver01/data/sn83016844/00542865349/1949063001/1258.xml":{"full_text":"Thursday, June 30, 1949\nNews Bits\n(Continued from Page 3)\nMrs. Margaret Martin, who\nhas been visiting her sister and\nbrither-in-law, Mr. andd Mrs.\nJohnny Hutcherson, 419 E. 39\nStreet, left Monday, June 27,\nfor Chicago, where she will vi\nsit relatives and friends before\nreturning to her home in Jack\nson, Miss.\nRev. and Mrs. H. W. Botts\nreturned Tuesday. June 28th,\nfrom a motor trip to Memphis,\nTenn, where they atended the\nBaptis Sunday School and BY\nPU Congress. While they were\nthe guests of Mr. and Mrs. Le\nwis O. Swingler, former mem\nbers of Rev. Botts\u2019 church in\nLincoln, Neb. and school mates\nof Rev. Henry Botts, Jr. Mr.\nSwingler is now editor of the\nMemphis World and also edits\nthe Sphnix, a magazine devot\ned to the fraternal affairs of\nthe Alpha Phi Alpha Fratern.\nity.\n\nThe Men\u2019s Cluh of St. Thom\nas church will hold their an\nnual picnic at Powderhorn\nPark on July 10th. A full pro\ngram of games, races, and fam\nily fun has been planned for\nthe afternoon.\n\nMinnehaha Temple No. 129\nof the Daughter Elks will have\nthe installation of elected of\nficers July 7th with the Grand\nDeputy, Mrs. Rebecca Force,\nofficiating. Officers to be in\nstalled include Mrs. Mary Hud\nson, Daughter Ruler; Mrs. Ro\nwena Griffin, vice Daughter\nRuler; Mrs. Elizabeth Davis,\nassistant vice-Daughter Ruler;\nMrs. Lola aJckson, Gate Keep\ner; Mrs. Venius Daniels, Door\nKeeper; Mrs. Lenora Adair,\nChaplain; Mrs. Bertha Smith,\nEscort; Mrs. Myrtle Banks,\nfinancial secretary; Mrs. Ida\nMae Burrell, recording secre\ntary; Mrs. Lucille Woodard,\ntreasurer; Mrs. La\u00dfelle Davis,\nchairman of trustees; Mrs.\nCatherine Perkins and Mrs.\nGertrude Mitchell, trustees.\nRev. Louis Johnson, rector\nof St. Thomas Episcopal\nchurch announces that services\nduring the summer months will\nbe held at 8 am. and 9 a.m.\nbeginning Sunday morning,\nJuly 2, and continuing until\nfurther notice.\nMiss Jacquilyn Smith of St.\nPaul returned home from her\nvacation in Columbus, Ohio, on\nSaturday morning June 25.\nMr. and Mrs Jo\u00abeph Genne\nof Chicago, 111., returned home\nMonday, June 27, after spend-\ning the week-end as the house\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. Paul\nCurry. During their stay in\nthe city your columnist had the\npleasure of reading Mr* Gen\nna\u2019s recently completed novel\nwhich is still in manuscript\nform Thia powerful book\nshould make the \u201cbest seller\"\nlist when it rolls off the preses.\nEmmet Salisbury, chairman\nof the 1949 United Negro Col\nlege Campaign for Minneapo\nlis, extended invitations to a\nlarge group of Twin City per\nsons to atend the luncheon at\nthe Radison Hotel Spanish\nRoom Thursday, June 30. Pur\npose of the meeting was to in\nform all interested people of\nthe aim and objective of the\nUnited Negro College Fund,\nInc. Dr. J. W. Whiite, presi\ndent of Lane College, Jack\nson, Tenn., addressed the group\nand explained the work that is\nbeing done in the 31 Negro\nColleges and Universities who\nparticipate in the funds.\nThe \u201cJohnny-come latelys\"\nwho expected to get last min\nwho expected t<\u00bbN get last min-\nute reservations for the dinner\nmeeting and address of Ralph\nBunche, United Nations Med\niator for Palestine, were gen\nuinely disappointed to learn\nthat all available space had\nbeen reserved long in advance.\nThe deluge of calls forced the\nsponsoring organizations to o\npen the balcony of the Coffman\nMemorial Union to the public\nat 7:15, set up a public address\nsystem to other buildings on\nthe campus, and arrange for\nthe speech to be broadcast over\nthe WTCN network.\nJottings from my Utt Ie\nBlue Book\nAccording to our recent ex\nperience the much talked of\n\u201crecession\" must be on the\nway. A neat, put shabby man\nmade his way slowly from\nhouse to house asking for odd\njobs. As he turned hopelessly\n\nCOMPLIMENT FROM A FRIEND\nPAINT AND LINOLEUM\nReasonable For Your Cleanup Month\nIJYOLtm 44 cents per Yard\nFOK YOI R CLEAN UP WORK\nPAINT UP PAPER VP\nDrop in at our Store\nKINSLEY\u2019S PAINT STORE\n211 FtM KTH AVENUE SOUTH\nOr Call Atlantic 2677\nCleanup Greetings From A Friend\nTWIN CITY OBSERVER\naway from each door, shoulders\ndrooping, we felt a sinking pre\nmonition of \u201cthings to come\".\nWill the horrible employment\nsituation of the last depres\nsion be repeated? What hap\npened to all the \u201cbig money\"\nthat was in circulation during\nthe war years? Those who are\nstill riding the \u2018gravy train\u201d\nhad better be \u201cmaking hay\nwhile the sun shines.\u201d The\nabove metaphors may be mixed,\nbut the situation will be more\nmuddled that our similies if\nfortunate, prosperous people\ncontinue to squander their as\nsets. A hint to the wise should\nbe sufficient. Although we\nwere unable to confirm the re\nport this week, we understand\nthat Miss Alvedia Cassius, the\ndaughter of Mr. and Mrs. A.\nB. Cassius, well-known busi\nness partners in Minneapolis,\nwill be married to Mr. Lloyd\nSmith, University of Minnesota\nstudent, July 8. Hope to have\nall details in time for next\nissue of the Observer and Sun.\nWe certainly wish that i\nprominent members of our race\nwho insist on gaining unfavor\nable publicity in the daily\npress, would stop making broad\nstatements concerning the en\ntire Negro population in Amer\nica. Since this is democracy\nupholding and permitting free\ndom of speech Paul Robeson\n(Continued on Page 8)\n\"...the beer\nFil that apeak*\nJkfor itsoH 1\n1623 NICOLLET AVENL\u2019K\nHatches Cleaned at\nWILLIAMSON\u2019S JEWELRY\n1715 EAST FKANKLIN AVENUE\nGuaranteed One Year\nBIERMAN\u2019S ICE CREAM\n9/5 East Franklin Avenue\nLOUUKT \u00abI 7 Kea.: KENWOOD 7704\nBIG CHRISTY\nUSED CARS BOUGHT AND SOLD\nH U. CH Hl STEN SON 2520 Nicollet Avenue\nStop and Shop at\nFranklin Furniture\n1535 EAST FRAN KUN AVENUE\nNew and Used Furniture of All Needs\nFor Your Home\nSAVE DOU